      <h1>XRP ETF - Everything You Need to Know</h1>
      <p class="post-lead">The XRP ETF landscape is evolving rapidly. Multiple asset managers have filed for spot XRP ETFs, following the success of Bitcoin and Ethereum ETFs. Here is where things stand and what it means for the XRP Ledger.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="post-body">
      <h2>What is an XRP ETF</h2>
      <p>An XRP Exchange-Traded Fund (ETF) is a regulated investment product that tracks the price of XRP and trades on traditional stock exchanges. It allows institutional and retail investors to gain exposure to XRP without directly holding the cryptocurrency -- no wallets, no private keys, no exchanges. They buy and sell shares through their existing brokerage accounts just like stocks.</p>

      <h2>Why XRP ETFs matter</h2>
      <p>ETFs are the bridge between traditional finance and crypto. Bitcoin ETFs attracted over $50 billion in inflows within their first year. An XRP ETF would:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Open institutional access:</strong> Pension funds, endowments, and wealth managers can allocate to XRP through familiar regulated vehicles</li>
        <li><strong>Increase liquidity:</strong> ETF market makers provide continuous two-sided markets, tightening spreads</li>
        <li><strong>Boost legitimacy:</strong> SEC-approved products signal regulatory acceptance</li>
        <li><strong>Drive on-chain activity:</strong> ETF custodians hold real XRP, increasing demand for on-chain settlement and infrastructure</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Current XRP ETF filings</h2>
      <p>Several major asset managers have filed or expressed interest in XRP ETF products. The SEC review process typically takes 240 days from filing, with multiple comment periods and potential delays. The Ripple vs SEC settlement in 2024 removed the largest regulatory overhang, making XRP ETF approval significantly more likely.</p>
      <p>Key filings include applications from Grayscale (conversion of the existing XRP Trust), 21Shares, Bitwise, and Canary Capital. Some jurisdictions outside the US already have XRP exchange-traded products listed on regulated exchanges.</p>

      <h2>Timeline and expectations</h2>
      <p>The SEC has a structured review process for ETF applications:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Filing:</strong> Asset manager submits 19b-4 form to the SEC</li>
        <li><strong>Federal Register:</strong> Published for public comment (21 days)</li>
        <li><strong>Review period:</strong> SEC has 45 days to approve, deny, or extend</li>
        <li><strong>Extensions:</strong> Can extend up to 240 days total from Federal Register date</li>
        <li><strong>Decision:</strong> Approve, deny, or begin proceedings for further review</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Market analysts generally expect XRP ETF decisions in 2025-2026, following the precedent set by Bitcoin and Ethereum ETF approvals.</p>

      <h2>Impact on the XRP Ledger</h2>
      <p>An approved XRP ETF would significantly increase demand for XRPL infrastructure. ETF custodians need reliable, full-history API access for:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Real-time price feeds:</strong> Continuous market data from the XRPL DEX</li>
        <li><strong>Settlement verification:</strong> Confirming XRP deposits and withdrawals on-chain</li>
        <li><strong>Audit trails:</strong> Full transaction history for compliance and reporting</li>
        <li><strong>Reserve proof:</strong> Verifying custodial holdings against on-chain balances</li>
      </ul>
      <p>This is exactly the kind of infrastructure XRPL Stream provides -- full-history API access, real-time WebSocket streaming, and enterprise-grade reliability across 21 globally distributed nodes.</p>

      <h2>Futures vs spot ETFs</h2>
      <p>There is an important distinction between futures-based and spot ETFs. Futures ETFs track XRP price through derivative contracts and do not hold actual XRP. Spot ETFs hold real XRP in custody, which creates direct demand for the asset and requires on-chain infrastructure. Spot ETFs are generally preferred by investors because they track the underlying asset more accurately and avoid the costs of rolling futures contracts.</p>

      <h2>International XRP products</h2>
      <p>While the US ETF process gets the most attention, XRP exchange-traded products already exist in several markets. European exchanges list XRP ETPs (Exchange-Traded Products) that function similarly to ETFs. These products have been available for several years and provide a template for how US-listed products might be structured.</p>

      <h2>Building for the ETF era</h2>
      <p>Whether you are building custodial infrastructure, compliance tools, or analytics dashboards for the institutional XRP market, XRPL Stream provides the API foundation. Full transaction history from genesis, real-time ledger streaming, and the reliability that institutional applications require.</p>

